<p><img src="/cob/fig8.PNG" alt="Figure 8" /></p>

<p>The two \(\color{#FA8072}{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}}\) in each Model do not label the same data point! Likewise, \(\color{#CCCCFF}{\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}}\) points to <img src="/cob/body1.PNG" width="50" height="40" /> in Model 1, but does not point to it in Model 2.</p>

<p>This is because \(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\) no longer has the same meaning in Model 2 as it did in Model 1. The <strong>meaning</strong> of a vector depends on its basis vectors.</p>

<p>In Model 1, \(\color{#FA8072}{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}}\) pointed to <img src="/cob/face1.PNG" width="50" height="40" /> because it‚Äôs supposed to mean ‚Äúhas a face with unit 1‚Äù. In Model 2, \(\color{#FA8072}{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}}\) points to ?? because it‚Äôs supposed to mean ‚Äúlikely to be a cat with unit 1‚Äù.[^1]</p>

<p>[^1] What does it mean to have 1 unit of ‚Äúlikely a cat?‚Äù For our example, we generalize to allow any ‚Äòprobabilistic‚Äô measurement to be used, as long as having X+1 units means ‚Äòit is more likely to be‚Äù than having X units.</p>

<!---* note that [body size 1] is present in Model 2, even though it's missing [face length]. In other words, it's [body size 1] + 0 * [face length 1]. This means that any data point which only contains a body of size 1 is seen as [meaning in terms of basis jk]--->

